We don't pick up Messenger based actions since that data is not released to the public. We focus on public data and curbing the issue of false positives pushing an artist to the top (fake bots, plays, followers, etc). It'd be interesting to work with @TheBotPlatform !
Well, good luck! Plenty of room for all types of platforms these days.
however, messenger as a distribution channel… I’m unsure of another channel that has most outbound messaging read within 1 minute
if you are trying to mimic an artist by using a bot, and trying to “lie”, then yes absolutely, this won’t work
it depends on what level of engagement you’re attempting to do, and what the bot “does”, we always recommend a hybrid approach
Major brands are also using bots and it seems to be helping them and their customers too :) you might be surprised by the results
There’s definitely an age group algorithm for bot engagement (I’m admittedly way outside of that group) but personally I want to engage with the artist or an actual rep.
Major brands are also using actual social media managers (i.e. people) and it seems to be boosting brand confidence or at least real engagement across their platforms. (See: @Wendys @MoonPie )

Because messenger is known or perceived as being an invader of privacy. People don’t want to use it to communicate with people they know let alone AI. Also, bots in general have taken a bad rap this year.
also, I’m not sure why you say it will be a hard sell, we’re seeing huge numbers of engagement
yep correct, our bots are on messenger, and are opt-in, they aren’t for faking comments etc
Ah, got it. While opt in approval is necessary, it’s gonna be a hard sell but, yes, working through messenger will won’t cause conflict between the platforms.

TBP primarily works within @messenger rather than through Facebook posts, and requires an opt in for interactions. It's likely that these Messenger-based actions wouldn't be picked up on by Asaii, and that they'd also be from real people. Thoughts, @asaii_inc @TheBotPlatform ?
